Thereafter, on 22 November 2004 Applicant applied to have the settlement agreement of December 2003 confirmed and made a consent order in terms of section 49D(2)(a) of the Act.\~  The AHF complainants, acting in an apparent effort to protect their right to pursue their complaint before the Tribunal, opposed the granting of the order.\~  The basis of their opposition is, however, no longer relevant, in view of the fact that on 2 March 2006 - and whilst the application was being argued - they withdrew both their complaint referral and their opposition to the granting of the consent order.}
\par \pard\plain \s17\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult0\qj{\rtlch \ltrch
\~ }
\par \pard\plain \s17\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult0\qj{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
While the application was still being argued as an opposed matter before the Tribunal at its hearing on the 2nd\~ of March 2005, the Tribunal, }{\i\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
mero motu}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
 raised an issue which it has consistently characterised as a point of jurisdiction.\~ \~  Applicant then filed additional heads of argument on this point and the Tribunal heard oral submissions from the applicant at a subsequent hearing exactly a year later to the day.}
\par \pard\plain \s17\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult0\qj{\rtlch \ltrch
\~ }
\par \pard\plain \s17\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
The Tribunal found that the December 2003 agreement was entered into at time when the one-year period for referral to it by the Commission had not yet expired.\~  However, the application in terms of section 49D was brought after the expiry of the one year period, at a time after the Commission was deemed to have non-referred the complaint. In its \'93Reasons\'94 for refusing the application, the Tribunal states that the question \'93asked of the Applicant was whether the Commission may be party to an application for a consent order at a point in time when it is no longer legally entitled to bring a complaint referral in respect of the complaint that forms the subject matter of the consent order\'94.}
\par \pard\plain \s17\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch
\~ }
\par \pard\plain \s17\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
The Commission was cited as a respondent in the application for a consent order.\~  Not surprisingly, as it was a party to the agreement, it did not oppose the application.\~  Nor was it\~  present\~  when the point raised was argued.\~  The Tribunal notes that \'93we do not have the benefit of its view on the point of law\'94.}
\par \pard\plain \s17\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch
\~ }
\par \pard\plain \s17\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
The first issue addressed by Applicant before the Tribunal was whether it, rather than the Commission, may make the application as had happened in this instance.\~  The Tribunal recorded that \'93[i]t has been normal practice for the Commission to bring this type of application. We need not decide this issue, although we will assume in the applicant\'92s favour that it is entitled to do so\'94.\~  I will revert to that issue later in this judgment.}
\par \pard\plain \s17\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch
\~ }
\par \pard\plain \s17\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
Applicant conceded that at the time when the application in terms of section 49D was brought, the Commission no longer had the power to refer a complaint.\~  However it argued that this does not mean that the Commission did not retain the power to \'93 agree on the terms of an appropriate order\'94.\~  The main thrust of Applicant\'92s argument both before the Tribunal and this Court relies on the language of the section 49D(1) which states:}
\par \pard\plain \s17\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch
\~ }
\par \pard\plain \s17\sb0\sa120\li676\ri676\lin676\rin676\fi0\sb0\sa0{\rtlch \ltrch
\'94}{\b\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs22\lang2057
If, during, on or after completion of the investigation of a complaint, the Competition Commission and the respondent agree on the terms of an appropriate order, the Competition Tribunal, without hearing any evidence, may confirm that agreement as a consent order in terms of section 58(1) (b).\'94}
\par \pard\plain \s17\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult0\qj{\rtlch \ltrch
\~ }
\par \pard\plain \s17\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
Applicant submits that the plain meaning of section 49D(1) is that\~  the agreement has to be reached \'93during, on or after\'94 the investigation but that neither that section, nor any other states when the application to confirm has to be made.\~  Applicant argues that there is no warrant to \'93read in\'94 words which limited the time by which the application to confirm has to be made and that there are safeguards in the Act to ensure that the complainants are not prejudiced.\~ \~  }
\par \pard\plain \s17\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch
\~ }
\par \pard\plain \s17\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
The Tribunal after analysing the scheme of the Act - and in particular, sections 49D and 50 - concluded that the word \'93after\'94 as it appears in section 49D(1) did include the power to reach and agreement after the investigation was completed, but that the section did \'93not contemplate any situation after the investigation, but only one where the Commission has retained its title to prosecute, by referring the complaint.\'94\~  }
\par \pard\plain \s17\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch
\~ }
\par \pard\plain \s17\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
The basis of the Tribunal\'92s decision is that:}
\par \pard\plain \s17\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch
\~ }
\par \pard\plain \s17\sb0\sa120\li676\ri676\lin676\rin676\fi0\sb0\sa0{\rtlch \ltrch
\'93}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs22\lang2057
the Commission must retain its title to prosecute at the time a consent order application has been launched to avoid it facing prosecutorial impotence if the Tribunal does not sanction its bargain with the respondent.\~  It can retain this title to prosecute either (a) by having the consent application considered during the one year period or an extended period or (b) after this period, provided it has referred the complaint to the Tribunal during the period thus preserving that right.\~  The legislature intended that once a matter had been non-referred by the Commission it washed its hands of the matter and had no further right or interest in the complaint including the right to settle it by way of a consent order.\'94}
\par \pard\plain \s17\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult0\qj{\rtlch \ltrch
\~ }
\par \pard\plain \s17\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
The Tribunal expressed the view that:}
\par \pard\plain \s17\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch
\~ }
\par \pard\plain \s17\sb0\sa120\li676\ri676\lin676\rin676\fi0\sb0\sa0{\rtlch \ltrch
\'93}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs22\lang2057
Thus, the power to prosecute and the power to settle are coextensive; once the former is lost so is the latter.\~  }
\par \pard\plain \s17\sb0\sa120\li676\ri676\lin676\rin676\fi0\sb0\sa0{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs22\lang2057
Thus, the power to prosecute and the power to settle are coextensive; once the former is lost so is the latter.\~  This is not a case of having to read in language into section 49D(1).\~  If one follows the procedural evolution of a complaint - how the Commission enjoys the monopoly power to prosecute and how it can lose this right to a complainant \'96 then one need not read in words to the section, one simply follows the schema and logic of the Act to appreciate that the legislature never contemplated conferring the power to settle to exist independently of the power to prosecute.\~  It is precisely for this reason that the Commission is given such a long period to investigate a complaint and to apply to extend it.\~  It must during this period of investigation decide whether to refer or settle a complaint.\~  If it refers it can of course settle it later.\~  What it may not do is to investigate, decide not to refer or settle and then at some later time decide it should enter into a settlement agreement for a consent order.\~  Nor should it, as happened in this case, enter into some contract (as opposed to a consent agreement contemplated in section 49D) with a respondent not to prosecute further, in return for some }{\i\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs22\lang2057
quid pro quo}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs22\lang2057
, unless it fully appreciates the legal implications of doing this.\'94}
\par \pard\plain \s17\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult0\qj{\rtlch \ltrch
\~ }
\par \pard\plain \s17\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
In support of its finding the Tribunal pointed to what it considered to be the undesirable results of accepting\~  Applicant\'92s interpretation of the Act. }
\par \pard\plain \s17\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch
\~ }
\par \pard\plain \s17\sb0\sa120\li676\ri676\lin676\rin676\fi0\sb0\sa0{\rtlch \ltrch
\'93}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs22\lang2057
One can easily see what absurdities would result if the title to prosecute and settle were not coextensive.\~  In the first place there is the fact that the Commission is left in a position of a contracting party not a prosecuting party in approaching settlement negotiations with the respondent, which cannot be in the public interest.\~  The ability to approach a settlement negotiation with the threat of proceeding is vital to a proper bargaining process.\~  A further concern is that the only time a consent order would be likely, after the title to prosecute has lapsed, is when a respondent faces a complainant in a non-referral situation or a new complaint based on a previous complaint that was not prosecuted.\~  The respondent, anxious to constrain the complainant\'92s range of remedies, then enters into a consent order with the Commission, the effect of which is to limit the private complainant\'92s remedies to those contemplated in section 49D(4).\~  Now of course that presupposes that the Commission will allow itself to be used to those ends.\~ \~  However, the expedient motive of a respondent may not always be that transparent to the Commission, especially if it was not a complaint that it referred, and it may be persuaded that the complainant is unreasonably pursuing the respondent and that a good settlement is available to the Commission even in this case it had not sought to prosecute.\~  The legislature never contemplated placing the Commission in this sort of situation as a settler of last resort \'96 once it lost its title to prosecute the fate of the litigation is left to the private complainant and the respondent to resolve.\~  Nor as a matter of public policy is it desirable that a body charged with policing legislation be left with a residual power to settle when its primary power to prosecute is lost. }
\par \pard\plain \s17\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult0\qj{\rtlch \ltrch
\~ }
\par \pard\plain \s17\sb0\sa120\li676\ri676\lin676\rin676\fi0\sb0\sa0{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs22\lang2057
The applicant\'92s interpretation would also be extremely unfair to the private complainant.\~  The latter is entitled to proceed with a complaint referral on the assumption that the field is now open to it and that the Commission had not entertained the possibility of entering into a consent agreement with the respondent, otherwise it would have done so before non\'96referring the complaint.\~  It might spend vast resources on prosecuting its complaint only to find that it is robbed at the post by a subsequent deal between the Commission and the respondent.\~  On our interpretation this would not arise because the settlement would have had to occur during the time that the Commission retained its prerogative to prosecute.\'94}
\par \pard\plain \s17\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult0\qj{\rtlch \ltrch
\~ }
\par \pard\plain \s17\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
The Tribunal concluded its reasons as follows:}
\par \pard\plain \s17\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult0\qj{\rtlch \ltrch
\~ }
\par \pard\plain \s17\sb0\sa120\li676\ri676\lin676\rin676\fi0\sb0\sa0{\rtlch \ltrch
\~ \'93}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs22\lang2057
For this reason we find that although the settlement in this matter was concluded during the period when the Commission had retained its title to prosecute the complaint, the application for the consent order was made after this period \'96 a time when we find that the Commission no longer retains the right to prosecute and hence no right to conclude, revise or amend a consent agreement. Without the Commission retaining this power, we have no jurisdiction to make the agreement that was entered into in December 2003 into a consent order. The application accordingly fails.}
\par \pard\plain \s17\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult0\qj{\rtlch \ltrch
\~ }
\par \pard\plain \s17\sb0\sa120\li676\ri676\lin676\rin676\fi0\sb0\sa0{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs22\lang2057
Given the considerable public interest there has been in the settlement between the Commission and the respondent we need to stress that our decision not to grant the consent order is a technical one, based on the timing of the application.\~  Were this consent application to have been made at a time when the Commission retained its title to prosecute, we would have seen no bar to granting it.\~  It would seem that the reason the December 2003 agreement was not made a consent order at the relevant time of its conclusion was that there was a difference of legal opinion between the applicant and the Commission about whether it was required to state the section of the Act it had contravened.\~  The Commission it appears has changed its view on this matter and now no longer as a matter of policy requires such an admission to be made. We are not called upon to determine whether such a policy is correct in law, but we mention this only to indicate that it may well be that technical concerns of the Commission, as opposed to tactical machinations on the part of the applicant, explain the absence of an application for a consent order at the relevant time.\'94}
\par \pard\plain \s17\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult0\qj{\rtlch \ltrch
\~ }
\par \pard\plain \s17\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult0\qj\li676\ri0\lin676\rin0\fi0{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
In his argument before this Court, }{\i\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
Mr Unterhalter}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
 SC (who appeared for Applicant together with Mr }{\i\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
Cockrell}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
 and Mr }{\i\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
Gotz}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
) emphasised three points.}
\par \pard\plain \s17\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult0\qj{\rtlch \ltrch
\~ }
\par \pard\plain \s17\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult0\qj{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
Firstly, he contended\~  that the provisions of section 49D(1) are clear and unequivocal.\~  The Commission can enter into a settlement agreement \'93}{\i\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
during, on or after completion of the investigation of a compliant}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
.\'94\~  The plain meaning of these words does not limit the time during which the Commission can conclude a settlement agreement.\~  Indeed, it can do so after a referral to the Tribunal and right up until the Tribunal announces its findings.}
\par \pard\plain \s17\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult0\qj{\rtlch \ltrch
\~ }
\par \pard\plain \s17\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
Section 49D has two jurisdictional requirements that must be satisfied before the Tribunal may grant an order in terms of the section.\~  They are:}
\par \pard\plain \s17\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult0\li676\ri0\lin676\rin0\fi0{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
-\~ \~ \~ \~ \~ \~  the Commission and the respondent must have agreed the terms of an appropriate order;}
\par \pard\plain \s17\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult0\li676\ri0\lin676\rin0\fi0{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
-\~ \~ \~ \~ \~ \~  the agreement must have been reached \'93}{\i\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
during, on or after the completion of the investigation of a complaint}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
\'94.}
\par \pard\plain \s17\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult0\qj{\rtlch \ltrch
\~ }
\par \pard\plain \s17\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
It was submitted that both requirements had been met and that the Tribunal had the necessary jurisdiction to grant an order confirming the settlement agreement.}
\par \pard\plain \s17\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch
\~ }
\par \pard\plain \s17\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
Secondly, there was no warrant, in law, to read in words that limited the clear meaning of section 49D(1) of the Act.}
\par \pard\plain \s17\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch
\~ }
\par \pard\plain \s17\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
Thirdly, the anomalies relied upon by the Tribunal were more apparent than real.\~  Even where the complainant pursued the complaint, the Commission had the right to appear and participate in the hearing (Section 53(1)(a).\~  It was, therefore, not rendered impotent.}
\par \pard\plain \s17\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch
\~ }
\par \pard\plain \s17\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
The legislature granted the right to the complainant to pursue its complain where there is a non-referral to ensure that it is not prejudiced.}
\par \pard\plain \s17\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch
\~ }
\par \pard\plain \s17\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult0\qj{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
Recognising that the Commission has a role to represent the public interest in cases of an alleged prohibited practice, }{\i\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
Mr Unterhalter}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
 submitted that the complainant who pursues a complain after a non-referral, has both a private and a public role.}
\par \pard\plain \s17\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult0{\rtlch \ltrch
\~ }
\par \pard\plain \s17\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
In order to determine the questions raised in the review and appeal - which are in both cases the same questions - it is necessary to examine\~  the provisions of the Act.}
\par \pard\plain \s17\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch
\~ }
\par \pard\plain \s17\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult0{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
Part C of Chapter 5 of the Act deals with the complaint\~  procedures and investigation of alleged prohibited practices.\~  A complaint may be initiated by the Commissioner }{\i\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
mero motu}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
 or as a result of information or a complaint submitted by \'93any person\'94 to the Commission. (Section 49B(1)and (2)).\~  The Commissioner is obliged to direct an inspector to investigate the complaint \'93as soon as possible\'94 (Section 49B(3)).\~  The investigative procedures and powers are found in Parts A and B of Chapter 5 of the Act. }
\par \pard\plain \s17\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult0{\rtlch \ltrch
\~ }
\par \pard\plain \s17\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs24\lang2057
Section 49C provides that an interim order may \'93at any time\'94 be granted by the Tribunal at the instance of a complainant in respect of a prohibited practice.}
\par \pard\plain \s17\sb0\sa120{\rtlch \ltrch
\~ }
\par \pard\plain \s17\sb0\sa120\sl360\slmult0{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
Section 50 deals with the outcome of a complaint.\~  The provisions recognise and give effect to the fact that the Commission is empowered and, indeed, directed to investigate and evaluate alleged contraventions of Chapter 2 of the Act which deals with prohibited practices. }{\i\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
Per contra}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
, the Tribunal is empowered to adjudicate on prohibited practices (See: }{\b\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
Simelane & Others NNO v Seven-Eleven Corporation SA (Pty) Ltd & Another}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang2057
 2003 (3) SA 64 (SCA) paras. 55 and 56).}
